WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.437
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.914 --> 00:00:06.580
CHIP CONLEY: Hi.

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:09.140
Let's start by saying I
apologize for a little bit

00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:11.030
of a hoarse throat.

00:00:11.030 --> 00:00:12.800
Yeah, you go on a book
tour, and you lose

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:15.470
things, including your voice.

00:00:15.470 --> 00:00:19.280
So I'm going to start with
about a 10-minute talk

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.690
that I gave two weeks ago at
TED headquarters in New York,

00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:27.050
and it goes on the ted.com
website a week from today.

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:28.730
So this is a 10-minute talk.

00:00:28.730 --> 00:00:30.784
Then I'll talk a
little bit more about,

00:00:30.784 --> 00:00:32.409
what does it mean to
be a modern elder?

00:00:32.409 --> 00:00:34.520
What are the qualities of
a what a modern elder--

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:36.791
what are the qualities that
a modern elder exhibits?

00:00:36.791 --> 00:00:38.540
And then I'll talk a
little bit about what

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:41.690
I think companies can
do to actually foster

00:00:41.690 --> 00:00:45.320
more intergenerational
collaboration and wisdom.

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:46.370
Sound good?

00:00:46.370 --> 00:00:48.000
And then we'll do a Q&amp;A.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.710
All right, so it
was my third day

00:00:51.710 --> 00:00:56.390
on the job at a hot Silicon
Valley startup in early 2013.

00:00:56.390 --> 00:01:00.320
I was more than twice the
age of the dozen engineers

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:01.191
in the room.

00:01:01.191 --> 00:01:02.690
I had been brought
into the company,

00:01:02.690 --> 00:01:05.360
because I was a seasoned
expert in my field,

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:09.020
but in that particular
room, I felt like a newbie

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:10.970
amongst the tech geniuses.

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:13.760
So I did my best
to be invisible.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:18.050
And then the 25-year-old wizard,
who was leading the meeting,

00:01:18.050 --> 00:01:21.950
turned to me and asked,
if you shipped a feature,

00:01:21.950 --> 00:01:25.940
and no one used it,
did it really ship?

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:27.980
Ship a feature?

00:01:27.980 --> 00:01:29.000
Whoa, oy vey.

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:34.910
I realized Chip was in
deep shit, because I

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:38.870
had no idea what he
was talking about.

00:01:38.870 --> 00:01:41.060
After an awkward
silence, he mercifully

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:45.140
moved on to someone else,
and I slid down in my chair,

00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:48.110
and I couldn't wait for
that meeting to end.

00:01:48.110 --> 00:01:52.420
That was my introduction to
Airbnb five and 1/2 years ago.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:56.330
I had been invited by the
three millennial co-founders

00:01:56.330 --> 00:02:01.310
to join the company to help
them take this small tech

00:02:01.310 --> 00:02:03.530
startup, fast-growing
tech startup,

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:06.410
and turn it into a
global hospitality brand,

00:02:06.410 --> 00:02:10.669
but also to be the
in-house mentor for Brian

00:02:10.669 --> 00:02:12.620
Chesky, the CEO.

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:14.600
So all that sounded
good, because I'd

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:18.700
spent, from age 26 to 52, being
a boutique hotel entrepreneur,

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:21.320
and I'd amassed a lot of
hospitality knowledge.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:23.900
But after my first
week at Airbnb,

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:26.660
I realized that the
brave new home-sharing

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:31.160
world didn't need most of my old
school bricks and mortar hotel

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:33.080
insights.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:35.690
A stark reality rocked me.

00:02:35.690 --> 00:02:38.690
What do I have to offer
these young people?

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:40.650
I've never worked
in a tech company.

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:43.040
I'm 52 years old, and I'd
never worked at a tech company

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.140
at that point.

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:48.500
I was reporting to someone
21 years younger than me--

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:49.220
Brian.

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:51.230
But I was also
supposed to mentor him.

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:54.410
I was the head of global
hospitality and strategy.

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:56.630
Five and 1/2 years
ago, I had never

00:02:56.630 --> 00:03:00.980
heard of the sharing economy,
nor did I have an Uber or Lyft

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:02.630
app on my phone.

00:03:02.630 --> 00:03:06.410
This was not my natural habitat.

00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:10.400
But I could have gone
off and run for the hills

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:14.810
or made fun or cast judgment
on these young geniuses.

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:19.040
But instead, I decided to
turn judgment into curiosity

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:21.800
and imagine how I could
match my wise eyes

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:24.060
with their fresh eyes.

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:26.320
I sort of imagined myself a--

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:29.810
or fancied myself a
modern Margaret Mead

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:33.470
amongst the millennials, sort
of a cultural anthropologist.

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:37.640
And I quickly learned that
I had as much to offer them

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:40.342
as they did to me.

00:03:40.342 --> 00:03:42.050
But the more I thought
about it, the more

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:46.640
I really noticed that we often--

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.670
the way we operate as
respective generations,

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:53.420
we often operate almost
like isolated countries

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:55.160
on the same continent.

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:57.800
Yes, we share borders,
but we don't necessarily

00:03:57.800 --> 00:03:59.660
trust each other enough
to sometimes share

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:01.490
our respective wisdom.

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:03.860
Looking at the modern
workplace, I've

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:07.850
come to believe that
creating a pipeline

00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:11.510
or opening up a pipeline
of intergenerational wisdom

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:16.670
could be the trade agreement
of our time in the workplace.

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:21.010
Almost 40% of us today have a
boss that's younger than us,

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:24.230
and that's only
growing as a number.

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:27.750
Power is cascading, and I
feel silly actually saying

00:04:27.750 --> 00:04:30.250
this part of the speech, because
you know it here at Google,

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:34.110
but power is cascading to young
people faster than ever before.

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:34.730
Why?

00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:37.280
Because we are growing
in our reliance

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:41.180
on digital intelligence,
what's called DQ.

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:44.000
We have young people starting
companies in their early 20s.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.390
They become global giants
by their 30th birthday.

00:04:47.390 --> 00:04:52.070
And yet somehow, we expect
these young, brilliant digital

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:56.870
leaders to miraculously embody
the relationship wisdoms

00:04:56.870 --> 00:04:59.960
and leadership skills
we older workers

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:02.390
have had decades to learn.

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:05.840
It's hard to microwave
your leadership skills

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:08.120
and emotional intelligence.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:11.930
We have ample evidence that
gender and ethnically diverse

00:05:11.930 --> 00:05:14.540
teams are often more effective.

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:17.810
But what about age?

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:19.770
It's a really
important question,

00:05:19.770 --> 00:05:22.010
and it's one of the
questions I posed

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:24.710
a lot to various companies,
because today, we

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:27.890
unintentionally have five
generations in the workplace

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:28.949
for the very first time.

00:05:28.949 --> 00:05:30.740
So maybe it's time to
get a little bit more

00:05:30.740 --> 00:05:34.100
intentional about
how we work together.

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:35.630
A number of European
studies have

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:41.360
shown that age-diverse
teams can be more effective,

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:45.620
and yet only 8% of companies
that have a diversity

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:48.140
and inclusion
program have expanded

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:50.300
that program or
strategy to include

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:53.630
age as just as important
of a demographic as, say,

00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:55.370
gender or race.

00:05:55.370 --> 00:05:57.260
Maybe they didn't get the memo.

00:05:57.260 --> 00:05:59.330
The world is getting older.

00:05:59.330 --> 00:06:03.020
One paradox of our time is
that baby boomers are healthier

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:06.620
longer, vibrant, and we're
in the workplace longer,

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:10.110
and yet often feeling
less and less relevant.

00:06:10.110 --> 00:06:13.610
Some of us feel a little bit
like an old carton of milk

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:16.970
with an expiration date stamped
on our wrinkled foreheads.

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:23.370
For many workers in midlife,
this isn't just a feeling.

00:06:23.370 --> 00:06:26.670
It's actually a harsh
reality, if you lose your job,

00:06:26.670 --> 00:06:28.530
and the phone stops ringing.

00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:31.680
For many of us, we feel
like our experience

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:36.150
might be seen as a liability
more than an asset.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:38.580
Many of us have heard
the phrase, "60 is

00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:41.347
the new 40," physically, right?

00:06:41.347 --> 00:06:42.930
Well, when it comes
to Silicon Valley,

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:44.110
and it comes to
the digital world,

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:45.818
and when it comes,
frankly, more and more

00:06:45.818 --> 00:06:51.030
to the power in the workplace,
I believe 30 is the new 50.

00:06:51.030 --> 00:06:55.100
So if power is moving
10 years younger,

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:59.220
and we're going to live 10
years longer, do the math.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:02.340
A new 20-year irrelevancy
gap has been created

00:07:02.340 --> 00:07:04.440
for those of us in midlife.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:06.870
Midlife used to be
considered 45 to 65,

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:10.470
but now it's really expanded,
I think, to 35 to 75,

00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:11.910
because there's
people, especially

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:15.204
in the Valley, who start feeling
irrelevant in their mid 30s.

00:07:15.204 --> 00:07:17.370
And there's lots of people
who are going to work way

00:07:17.370 --> 00:07:20.120
past the traditional
retirement age of 65,

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:21.980
and they may work till
75, because if you're

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:25.140
going to live to 100, either
by choice or by necessity,

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:27.000
you may work longer.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.980
So that midlife marathon--

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:33.300
and by the way, as an aside,
the term, "midlife crisis,"

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:35.880
was created in
1965, but we haven't

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:39.600
done much in 53 years since
then to make it any better.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:41.450
OK, now it starts
getting better.

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:43.320
That's all the depressing stuff.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:45.300
Here's the good stuff.

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.370
Here's a bright spot.

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:51.360
Why is it that as we age,
we become a little wiser

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.440
about our humanity?

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:56.730
Our physical peak as
humans is probably our 20s,

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:59.430
or as adults is our 20s.

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:03.570
Our financial peak, salary-wise,
is 45 in Silicon Valley.

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:06.680
For the general population,
it's about 50 to 52.

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:11.220
But our emotional peak actually
happens in midlife and beyond,

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:13.860
because we start to
develop pattern recognition

00:08:13.860 --> 00:08:15.465
about ourselves and others.

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:22.207
So how do we actually-- oops--

00:08:22.207 --> 00:08:23.790
so the question is,
how do we actually

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:28.560
help companies tap into
that potential midlife

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:33.659
wisdom, while also nurturing
their young, brilliant digital

00:08:33.659 --> 00:08:34.559
natives?

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:37.230
I think the most successful
companies today will figure out

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:41.159
how to create a powerful
alchemy between the two.

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:43.830
Here's how the alchemy
worked for me at Airbnb.

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:48.210
I was assigned a sharp
young partner, Laura Hughes,

00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:51.900
to be my partner in creating
the hospitality department.

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:54.960
I oversaw about eight
different teams at Airbnb.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.660
Hospitality was one, strategy
was another, et cetera,

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.750
but I'll focus on
hospitality for now.

00:09:00.750 --> 00:09:03.570
Early on, Laura
Hughes, my partner,

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:07.440
saw that I was a little lost
when it came to technology,

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.330
and so she often sat right
next to me at meetings.

00:09:10.330 --> 00:09:12.330
And when I heard words
that I didn't understand,

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:15.840
I'd write her a note, and she
would be my tech translator.

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:19.680
She spent four years here at
Google before a year and a half

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:21.630
at Airbnb when I
met her, and she was

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:23.610
27 years old when I met her.

00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:25.960
Like many of her
millennial cohorts,

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:29.460
she had been elevated to a
role of being a manager way

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:32.670
before she ever had any
formal leadership training.

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:36.240
I don't care if you're in
the B2B world, the B2C world,

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:39.310
the C2c world, or the A2Z world.

00:09:39.310 --> 00:09:42.450
Business and organizations
are fundamentally H2H,

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:43.860
human to human.

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:47.850
And yet, Laura's approach
to leadership and management

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:49.890
had been formed in the
technocratic world.

00:09:49.890 --> 00:09:53.580
It was all about accountability
charts and business roadmaps

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:56.010
and metrics and
metrics and metrics.

00:09:56.010 --> 00:09:57.020
And that's not bad.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:00.640
I could get shot if I say that
too loudly here at Google.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:04.592
Not bad, but it needed to be
dosed with something else.

00:10:04.592 --> 00:10:07.050
What she said to me about a
month into the job is like, oh,

00:10:07.050 --> 00:10:11.700
my gosh, what I appreciate is
that you help us, as a team,

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:14.220
create a compelling
vision, and then

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:16.890
that becomes the North
Star for how we operate.

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:19.920
And she said, your
fact knowledge chip

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:22.440
isn't all that valuable here.

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:27.060
How many rooms a maid cleans
in an eight-hour shift doesn't

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:29.130
matter in the
home-sharing world,

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:33.030
but your process knowledge
is really valuable,

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.460
process knowledge
being you know how

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:39.270
to get things done based upon
understanding the underlying

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:41.580
motivations of
everyone in the room.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:43.766
And your organizationally
savvy enough,

00:10:43.766 --> 00:10:45.390
because you've been
around for a while,

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:49.110
to know how to get things
done in an organization.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:52.410
So as I spent more
time at Airbnb,

00:10:52.410 --> 00:10:57.090
I actually started to notice
that maybe a new kind of elder

00:10:57.090 --> 00:10:59.760
was emerging in the workplace.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:02.190
No, not the elder
of the past, who

00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:04.454
was regarded with reverence.

00:11:04.454 --> 00:11:06.120
There are only a few
places in the world

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:08.280
where that's still the case.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:12.240
No, this modern elder
actually was appreciated

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:16.500
for their relevance, their
ability to take timeless wisdom

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:19.350
and apply it to
modern day problems.

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.020
Maybe it's time that we
actually start valuing wisdom

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:23.730
as much as we do disruption.

00:11:23.730 --> 00:11:27.300
And I absolutely think it's time
we reclaim the word, "elder,"

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:29.730
but give it a modern twist.

00:11:29.730 --> 00:11:32.310
The modern elder is
as much an intern

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:35.340
as they are a mentor, because
they realize in a world that

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:38.610
is changing as quickly
as it is today,

00:11:38.610 --> 00:11:40.920
that it's important
that our beginner's

00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:44.670
mind and catalytic curiosity
allows them to create almost

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:48.240
like a life-affirming elixir
for both themselves and everyone

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:50.130
else.

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:53.370
We're very familiar
with intergen improv

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:55.340
in music and the arts.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:59.650
Think Tony Bennett and Lady
Gaga or Wynton Marsalis

00:11:59.650 --> 00:12:03.590
and the Young Stars of Jazz.

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:05.710
But in the business
world, we don't really

00:12:05.710 --> 00:12:08.170
have a language for this,
this kind of riffing off

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:11.630
of each other with
different generations.

00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:14.980
But we might often call
it mutual mentorship,

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:16.970
and mutual mentorship
is, frankly--

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:20.350
in my case, I was
getting Millennial DQ,

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:22.180
digital intelligence,
and what I was

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:28.351
offering back was Boomer EQ, but
it could be Gen X EQ as well.

00:12:28.351 --> 00:12:32.290
At Airbnb, I actually had a
dose of this kind of intergen

00:12:32.290 --> 00:12:35.320
reciprocity when
Laura and I took on,

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:37.810
along with our stellar
data science team,

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:41.050
the process of completely
remaking the Airbnb

00:12:41.050 --> 00:12:44.110
peer-to-peer review
system, based

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:47.260
upon Laura's analytical
mind and my sort of more

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:49.180
human-centered intuition.

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:52.900
With this powerful alchemy of
algorithm and people wisdom,

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:56.650
we were able to actually take
a relatively good program,

00:12:56.650 --> 00:12:58.390
the peer-to-peer
review system, and make

00:12:58.390 --> 00:13:01.660
it a great program that helped
our hosts better understand

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:03.940
the needs of our guests,
such that we actually

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:07.450
got Airbnb's guest satisfaction
level with our hosts

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:10.240
higher than the hotel
industry, substantially higher,

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:12.860
because we used the same
metric the hotel industry does.

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:17.380
So this is a great example of
high tech meeting high touch.

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:19.060
As a modern elder,
I also learned

00:13:19.060 --> 00:13:25.086
that I needed to intern
publicly and mentor privately.

00:13:25.086 --> 00:13:26.710
What I mean by that
is, like, you know,

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:29.020
nobody wants me telling them
in the middle of the meeting

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:30.269
that they did something wrong.

00:13:30.269 --> 00:13:31.330
I'm not their parent.

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:33.980
That's what their
parent might do.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:36.460
But what they really
appreciated was this.

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:38.890
And let me-- here's my
search engine [INAUDIBLE]..

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:41.620
Search engines are great
for giving us answers,

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:43.630
and over time, you may
actually, at Google,

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:46.390
get better and better at
even posing questions to us.

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:47.800
I don't know where that's going.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:49.520
I might ask Dan
in the back there.

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:52.570
But the bottom line
is you're great.

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:55.060
Google has all the
knowledge in the world,

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:59.680
and so answers come from
a place like Google.

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:05.970
But a beautifully posed
question asked by a wise elder

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:09.940
can actually unlock
someone's mind and heart

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:11.870
to all kinds of other things.

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:14.650
And so I actually do
believe that a wise elder,

00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:18.640
a modern elder can actually
have that finally attuned heart

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:20.860
and mind that can
actually open up

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:23.800
the possibilities for
someone younger than them.

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:26.560
Over time, to my
surprise, I had, actually,

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.980
over 100 people in the
organization asking

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:31.630
me to mentor them.

00:14:31.630 --> 00:14:34.780
It was not my job, not even
in my scope of work at all.

00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:37.930
But every time somebody
asked, I said yes.

00:14:37.930 --> 00:14:39.970
It was nuts, to be
honest with you,

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:42.040
but I loved it,
because what happened

00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:45.220
is I learned as much from
them as they did from me.

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:46.720
And that was the beauty of it.

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:49.840
In sum, Brian Chesky,
the CEO, asked

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:54.020
me to join Airbnb because
of my industry knowledge.

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:58.600
But what I really offered
was my well-earned wisdom.

00:14:58.600 --> 00:15:00.520
Peter Drucker, the
management theorist,

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:05.800
created the phrase or the term,
"knowledge worker," in 1959.

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:09.190
I think it's time we retire
the phrase, "knowledge worker,"

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:12.340
and replaced it with "wisdom
worker," because, really,

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:16.300
that's what we offer
in our humanity.

00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:18.760
With five generations in the
workplace for the first time,

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:21.460
we can either operate
like separate isolationist

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:26.740
countries, or we can find
a way to build bridges

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:29.060
across those
generational borders,

00:15:29.060 --> 00:15:31.990
so we can learn from people
both older and younger than us

00:15:31.990 --> 00:15:33.610
and delight in that.

00:15:33.610 --> 00:15:36.460
It's time, also, to switch up
our thinking about the physics

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:40.000
of wisdom, so it's not just
moving from old to young,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.190
but it's moving from
young to old as well.

00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:46.300
So in your life,
personally, who could you

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:50.920
reach out to to actually build a
mutual mentorship relationship?

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:54.070
And organizationally,
how do we create

00:15:54.070 --> 00:15:59.710
the conditions to foster more
of an intergenerational flow

00:15:59.710 --> 00:16:01.100
of wisdom?

00:16:01.100 --> 00:16:05.230
This is the new sharing
economy, in my opinion.

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:06.280
So that's my talk.

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:08.555
There you go.

00:16:08.555 --> 00:16:09.055
So--

00:16:09.055 --> 00:16:09.815
[APPLAUSE]

00:16:09.815 --> 00:16:10.650
Yeah, thank you.

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:19.730
So let me talk for
a few more minutes,

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:22.780
and then we'll open
up for questions.

00:16:22.780 --> 00:16:27.880
The idea of a
modern elder really

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:29.860
made me sick the
first time I heard it.

00:16:29.860 --> 00:16:32.140
Someone said, you're
like my elder.

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:35.620
I was like, you know,
what did I do wrong?

00:16:35.620 --> 00:16:37.930
Because "elder"
sounded like "elderly."

00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:42.670
And of course, here's the
thing is 50 years ago,

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:44.710
"elder" was elderly.

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:47.440
50 years ago, the average age
of when someone actually went

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:49.450
into a nursing home was 65.

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:51.670
Today, it's almost 85.

00:16:51.670 --> 00:16:57.710
So we have actually created
a new period of life.

00:16:57.710 --> 00:17:03.340
Longevity in the US in the
year 1900 was 47 years old.

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:06.369
By the year 2000,
it was 77 years old.

00:17:06.369 --> 00:17:09.819
We added three decades
to US average longevity

00:17:09.819 --> 00:17:12.790
in one century, but
we have done zero

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:15.190
to actually define this
period of life that

00:17:15.190 --> 00:17:19.940
is pre-elderly and midlife
and a little bit later.

00:17:19.940 --> 00:17:21.160
I'm 58 this month.

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:23.176
I'm absolutely right
in the middle of it.

00:17:23.176 --> 00:17:24.550
But as I said
earlier, I actually

00:17:24.550 --> 00:17:26.591
think there's a lot of
people in the middle of it

00:17:26.591 --> 00:17:28.810
in the sense that when
you have, especially

00:17:28.810 --> 00:17:31.660
in Silicon Valley, a growing,
young population of people who

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:34.690
are very smart, being
able to figure out,

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:39.880
how do you match that smart,
young talent with people

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:43.450
older, who might be able to
actually offer something, is,

00:17:43.450 --> 00:17:47.080
I think, one of the most
interesting HR and leadership

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:51.340
opportunities of the 21st
century in the workplace.

00:17:51.340 --> 00:17:52.830
What I'll say is that the book--

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:54.911
I think you're all
getting books, I guess.

00:17:54.911 --> 00:17:55.660
Yeah, yeah, maybe?

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:56.210
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:56.210 --> 00:17:57.120
We've got a few copies left.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:58.020
CHIP CONLEY: OK, there's
a few copies left.

00:17:58.020 --> 00:17:58.547
OK.

00:17:58.547 --> 00:18:00.130
Hopefully, you're
going to get a book.

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:02.936
And what you'll see is there
are four lessons in the book,

00:18:02.936 --> 00:18:04.810
and I'll just go through
this really quickly,

00:18:04.810 --> 00:18:07.770
and then I'll finish with just
one organizational thought,

00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:09.610
because I think
Google actually is

00:18:09.610 --> 00:18:12.010
a role model for the
organizational thought.

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:15.940
So the four lessons I learned
was, number one, evolve.

00:18:15.940 --> 00:18:17.260
If you're in midlife--

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:19.800
and I'm defining
midlife 35 to 75--

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.102
it's a wide definition--

00:18:22.102 --> 00:18:23.560
the number one
thing you need to be

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:28.750
able to do to be able to
rewire yourself and reframe

00:18:28.750 --> 00:18:31.600
your mastery is to evolve.

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:34.150
And "evolve" basically
means you actually

00:18:34.150 --> 00:18:37.240
need to be willing
to actually shed

00:18:37.240 --> 00:18:40.750
part of your historic identity
and your historical knowledge.

00:18:40.750 --> 00:18:42.590
It doesn't mean it
goes away forever.

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:44.650
It just means you don't
show up with that.

00:18:44.650 --> 00:18:47.980
I was the CEO of my own boutique
hotel company, as Karen said,

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:49.090
Joie de Vivre.

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:51.350
And we created 52 boutique
hotels, a few of them

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:51.850
down here.

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:56.110
Actually, we were the biggest
hotelier in Silicon Valley

00:18:56.110 --> 00:18:59.530
and San Francisco
or the Bay Area.

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:03.550
So I was a CEO for 24
years, took a company

00:19:03.550 --> 00:19:05.710
from one to 3,500 employees.

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:06.820
I sold it.

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:08.440
I had a couple years
off, and then I

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:09.898
was like, OK, what
am I doing next?

00:19:09.898 --> 00:19:13.330
And then Brian
Chesky approached me.

00:19:13.330 --> 00:19:17.760
If I had gone into that job
thinking of myself as the CEO,

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:19.090
it wouldn't have worked.

00:19:19.090 --> 00:19:21.100
Brian and I were lucky
enough, two nights ago,

00:19:21.100 --> 00:19:24.520
to be on stage at the
Marines Memorial Theater

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.100
with 500 people in the
audience giving a talk,

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:29.980
together, Brian and me, to
saying, how did this work?

00:19:29.980 --> 00:19:32.470
How did a millennial
and a modern elder

00:19:32.470 --> 00:19:35.740
come together to help
create a business

00:19:35.740 --> 00:19:38.690
plan that was able to flourish?

00:19:38.690 --> 00:19:43.480
So part of it was me
being willing to say,

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:45.860
I used to be the
sage on the stage,

00:19:45.860 --> 00:19:47.710
and now I'm the
guide on the side.

00:19:47.710 --> 00:19:50.360
And what that meant is I
had to right size my ego.

00:19:50.360 --> 00:19:53.110
I needed to realize that
the last thing Brian needed,

00:19:53.110 --> 00:19:56.110
as a leader 21 years
younger than me,

00:19:56.110 --> 00:20:01.600
was having me, in meetings,
say things that he

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:02.890
should be doing differently.

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:06.730
Obviously, that needed to
be the mentoring privately.

00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:09.160
But more than anything,
I need to also evolve

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:12.250
my knowledge, which has brought
me to the second lesson, which

00:20:12.250 --> 00:20:13.540
is to learn.

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:15.795
So a lot of times, people
in midlife need to evolve,

00:20:15.795 --> 00:20:18.170
but then they actually have
to say, I'm willing to learn.

00:20:18.170 --> 00:20:19.628
I'm going to be a
lifelong learner.

00:20:19.628 --> 00:20:22.780
I'm going to learn more now in
my 50s than I did in my 40s.

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:25.389
Now that breaks
conventional wisdom.

00:20:25.389 --> 00:20:27.680
There's an element that we
think, OK, as you get older,

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:30.490
you just have less to learn,
partly because it's almost

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:34.630
thought that you have a
bottle , and it's full.

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:35.820
I don't have anymore space.

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:38.430
There's no more space to
put more knowledge in it,

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:39.150
and that's--

00:20:39.150 --> 00:20:42.960
in terms of how our brains
work, that's not how it works.

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:46.170
So sometimes you have to pour
out a little bit also in order

00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:48.090
to make some extra room.

00:20:48.090 --> 00:20:49.930
So learning is a really
key part of that,

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:51.770
and that's chapter
5 in the book.

00:20:51.770 --> 00:20:53.815
And the third lesson I
learned was collaboration.

00:20:53.815 --> 00:20:55.690
And one of the things
that's so interesting--

00:20:55.690 --> 00:20:59.340
I love-- in the book, I do talk
about Project Aristotle, which

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:01.500
was the collaboration
project here,

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:04.620
or the study of what
makes successful teams

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:06.270
and effective teams.

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:08.520
Interesting thing just to
look at-- that collaboration

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:09.480
is so essential.

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:11.330
And yet in-- when
I joined Airbnb,

00:21:11.330 --> 00:21:13.260
one thing that was most
noticeable-- we were--

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:14.820
Karen and I were just talking
about meetings and studying

00:21:14.820 --> 00:21:16.470
meetings, what works
and what doesn't.

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:17.250
Oh, my gosh.

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:20.130
The meetings at Airbnb
were really, really hard

00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:23.500
to sit through, because they
weren't really well-organized,

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:25.660
and there was not a
collaborative spirit.

00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.200
There's a lot of evidence and
studies that's shown that,

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:30.990
frankly, put a couple
of women in the room,

00:21:30.990 --> 00:21:33.180
and put a couple older
people in the room,

00:21:33.180 --> 00:21:36.150
and it tends to lead
to-- not always--

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:38.340
to a more collaborative team.

00:21:38.340 --> 00:21:40.590
And it's partly because
there's a little more empathy.

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:41.900
Oh, she's laughing.

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:42.600
OK.

00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:44.230
Do you agree?

00:21:44.230 --> 00:21:44.730
Yes?

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:52.770
And I think what we need to
know about that is collaboration

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:55.800
is essential for any company.

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:58.860
And so one of the
things that I really

00:21:58.860 --> 00:22:01.020
heartily recommend to
people who are in midlife

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:04.560
and remake themselves is to
really speak to, how are they--

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:06.510
how do they use their
EQ, which can grow

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:09.240
with time, in a way that
actually shows that they have

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:10.890
collaboration skills?

00:22:10.890 --> 00:22:13.460
And then the fourth
lesson is counsel,

00:22:13.460 --> 00:22:15.960
and that's actually the lesson
that most people go to first.

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:17.340
You're older, and you
still feel like, well, I'm

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:18.400
here to advise people.

00:22:18.400 --> 00:22:19.920
I'm here to mentor people.

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:21.750
And honestly, if that's what
you're going to lead with,

00:22:21.750 --> 00:22:23.250
and you haven't done
the other three first,

00:22:23.250 --> 00:22:25.000
people will maybe think
that you're either

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.570
their preacher or their
parent, because you're going

00:22:27.570 --> 00:22:29.640
to actually maybe be lecturing.

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:31.140
And there's a
beautiful old phrase--

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:33.930
"knowledge speaks,
and wisdom listens."

00:22:33.930 --> 00:22:36.180
And one of the things that
a lot of people don't know,

00:22:36.180 --> 00:22:37.770
and I only learned
two months ago,

00:22:37.770 --> 00:22:41.340
is that the owl is
perceived as the wisest bird

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:43.020
or animal in the forest.

00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:43.800
Why?

00:22:43.800 --> 00:22:48.460
Because it has the most finely
attuned sense of hearing.

00:22:48.460 --> 00:22:50.910
So wisdom is about
listening, and it's

00:22:50.910 --> 00:22:54.630
about listening not just to
the story, but for the story.

00:22:54.630 --> 00:22:57.840
And the difference is for the
story gets beyond the literal.

00:22:57.840 --> 00:22:59.520
It allows you to
actually see, what

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:03.960
are the common threads that
you're hearing from the person?

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:08.460
In sum, because I started
writing this book,

00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:09.886
and I started feeling like, wow.

00:23:09.886 --> 00:23:11.260
I started
interviewing-- my story

00:23:11.260 --> 00:23:13.830
is unusual, because I was
asked by the founders at age 52

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:14.910
to join them.

00:23:14.910 --> 00:23:17.010
Most people at 52 are
not asked to join a tech

00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:18.590
company if they've never
have been in a tech community

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:19.290
before.

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:20.490
So I'm lucky.

00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:22.740
I went out, and I
interviewed 150 other people

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:25.350
and said, tell me
what your experience--

00:23:25.350 --> 00:23:27.150
most of the people in
their 40s and 50s--

00:23:27.150 --> 00:23:29.100
about being in midlife.

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:31.530
And I heard a lot of
anxiety and bewilderment.

00:23:31.530 --> 00:23:33.600
And I had a lot of people
saying, you know what?

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:36.310
I don't know how to
get through this time.

00:23:36.310 --> 00:23:39.600
And I started thinking about
it, and I said, man, you

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:44.680
know what's interesting is we
as a society have historically

00:23:44.680 --> 00:23:47.380
helped people through
transitional times

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:50.470
by creating rituals
or celebrations.

00:23:50.470 --> 00:23:53.145
Like with puberty,
it's bat mitzvah,

00:23:53.145 --> 00:23:55.180
bar mitzvah, quinceanera.

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:57.932
You're going to go from
adolescence to adulthood-- you

00:23:57.932 --> 00:23:59.140
have a commencement ceremony.

00:23:59.140 --> 00:24:00.477
You graduate from something.

00:24:00.477 --> 00:24:02.060
You actually are
going to get married.

00:24:02.060 --> 00:24:02.710
You have a wedding.

00:24:02.710 --> 00:24:03.730
You're going to have a baby.

00:24:03.730 --> 00:24:04.720
You have a baby shower.

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:05.553
You're going to die.

00:24:05.553 --> 00:24:06.370
You have a funeral.

00:24:06.370 --> 00:24:12.010
But between baby shower
and funeral, nada, nothing.

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:14.500
And back when the
longevity was 47,

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:17.790
it didn't matter,
because midlife was 24.

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:19.960
But midlife today is, who knows?

00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:23.410
Somewhere around 50, 55 maybe.

00:24:23.410 --> 00:24:24.780
Who knows?

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:28.060
And we have nothing to
address the transitions that

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:29.440
happen in midlife.

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:30.970
What are those transitions?

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:32.920
Well, you know, you
can lose a parent.

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:34.270
You could lose a spouse.

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:35.830
You could actually get divorced.

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:38.750
You can change job or
career or location.

00:24:38.750 --> 00:24:42.430
You can actually go through
empty nester syndrome,

00:24:42.430 --> 00:24:43.990
where the kids are gone.

00:24:43.990 --> 00:24:45.530
You go through menopause.

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:47.260
Men, we go through andropause.

00:24:47.260 --> 00:24:48.680
You don't even
know what that is.

00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:49.555
I'm going through it.

00:24:52.540 --> 00:24:54.400
All these things
happen, and there's

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:57.110
no transitional support.

00:24:57.110 --> 00:25:00.100
So long story short is I created
something called the Modern

00:25:00.100 --> 00:25:01.300
Elder Academy.

00:25:01.300 --> 00:25:03.102
I finally totally
embraced the word.

00:25:03.102 --> 00:25:04.810
Not only was it the
subtitle of the book,

00:25:04.810 --> 00:25:05.893
but I said, you know what?

00:25:05.893 --> 00:25:07.570
Modern elder-- I'll
be one of those,

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:09.130
and let's create an academy.

00:25:09.130 --> 00:25:14.020
So we did in Baja,
California, so in Mexico,

00:25:14.020 --> 00:25:16.590
just one hour north
of Cabo San Lucas.

00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:18.220
It's a three-acre
campus on the beach,

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:21.640
and we have people coming
from all over the world.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:24.130
We did a beta program of it
the first half of the year.

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:27.430
153 people went
through week-long

00:25:27.430 --> 00:25:29.862
and two-week long programs
that went really well.

00:25:29.862 --> 00:25:31.570
And 50% of the people
are on scholarship,

00:25:31.570 --> 00:25:32.736
so it's a social enterprise.

00:25:32.736 --> 00:25:33.790
It's not-- it's not--

00:25:33.790 --> 00:25:35.830
the purpose of it is
not to make money.

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:38.530
Last thought, before we
open up for questions--

00:25:38.530 --> 00:25:42.160
organizationally,
what can we do to help

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:46.990
foster more intergenerational
collaboration or more

00:25:46.990 --> 00:25:49.090
understanding of the
value of the modern elder?

00:25:49.090 --> 00:25:53.560
Two thoughts-- number one is one
thought is to start with, OK,

00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:56.290
if you have new hire
buddies in the company,

00:25:56.290 --> 00:25:59.650
consider how you actually match
people who don't look much

00:25:59.650 --> 00:26:00.650
alike--

00:26:00.650 --> 00:26:03.910
not gender, race,
age, et cetera.

00:26:03.910 --> 00:26:06.100
How do you help to
foster that, even

00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:08.590
in the early days of
someone joining a company?

00:26:08.590 --> 00:26:10.600
But the bigger idea I
have that really speak--

00:26:10.600 --> 00:26:11.766
and I have a bunch of ideas.

00:26:11.766 --> 00:26:14.560
Chapter 9 in the book
is full of 10 ideas

00:26:14.560 --> 00:26:17.539
that companies actually
could incorporate.

00:26:17.539 --> 00:26:19.330
But the one that relates
to Google is this.

00:26:19.330 --> 00:26:21.730
I know you have
20% time, which was

00:26:21.730 --> 00:26:23.560
supposed to be 80% plus 20%.

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:26.440
It's really 100%
plus 20%, right?

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:30.880
So the idea was, at Google,
engineers, especially who

00:26:30.880 --> 00:26:33.380
wanted to go out and
innovate, could actually

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:37.570
be given the opportunity to
work on innovation projects that

00:26:37.570 --> 00:26:38.620
might serve the company.

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:41.470
Great idea.

00:26:41.470 --> 00:26:45.430
What if we actually got a
little bit more intentional

00:26:45.430 --> 00:26:49.270
about asking questions on
employee surveys, questions

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:51.220
like the following--

00:26:51.220 --> 00:26:54.100
other than your boss or
someone on your team,

00:26:54.100 --> 00:26:59.150
who in the company do you look
to for advice or for wisdom?

00:26:59.150 --> 00:27:02.000
What if we could actually
start identifying

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.120
not just the spaces of
innovation in the company,

00:27:05.120 --> 00:27:09.350
but the spaces of wisdom and
who actually are perceived

00:27:09.350 --> 00:27:10.910
as the role models for that?

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:13.700
And then what if we actually,
knowing that information,

00:27:13.700 --> 00:27:15.590
started to develop
programs where

00:27:15.590 --> 00:27:18.140
people who have institutional
wisdom and knowledge,

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:19.460
have been in the company for--

00:27:19.460 --> 00:27:22.360
you pick the determining
amount of years.

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:24.230
At Procter and Gamble,
there is a program

00:27:24.230 --> 00:27:25.400
called the Mastery Program.

00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:27.170
It's 10 years.

00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:30.136
But at a tech company,
it might be five years.

00:27:30.136 --> 00:27:31.760
Once a person has
been there that long,

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:34.145
you have the ability,
if you choose to,

00:27:34.145 --> 00:27:38.910
to start moving into the modern
elder or the mastery program,

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:42.260
which allows you to actually
scope down a little bit what

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:44.964
you're working on and actually
allocate some of your time

00:27:44.964 --> 00:27:46.880
to things that would be
helpful to the company

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:48.620
around institutionalized wisdom.

00:27:48.620 --> 00:27:52.490
Could be in-house mentorship,
but in many cases,

00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:54.390
it could be actually
sitting-- and the way

00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:57.620
Procter and Gamble does it, you
actually go sit in on teams,

00:27:57.620 --> 00:27:59.480
and you actually
get joint teams,

00:27:59.480 --> 00:28:01.414
because if you have
collaboration skills,

00:28:01.414 --> 00:28:03.080
and if you have
institutionalized wisdom

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:05.960
about how Procter and
Gamble has innovated,

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:08.370
you actually offer
that to the teams.

00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:11.330
So it's just an idea,
because I really think that--

00:28:11.330 --> 00:28:14.330
frankly, if Brian said to me,
knowing that there were 100

00:28:14.330 --> 00:28:16.790
people that I was
mentoring over the course--

00:28:16.790 --> 00:28:19.460
not all at the same time, but
over the five and 1/2 years

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:21.620
I've been there--

00:28:21.620 --> 00:28:24.620
if Brian knew how much
time that was taking,

00:28:24.620 --> 00:28:26.720
and he knew I could
actually somehow scope down

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:29.450
my primary responsibilities
so that I could spend either

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:33.680
20% or maybe 50% my time
on just helping create

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:36.890
that invisible productivity,
which a modern elder can

00:28:36.890 --> 00:28:38.720
provide, because there's
a lot of evidence

00:28:38.720 --> 00:28:41.360
that if you are doing
this well, you're

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:42.620
not just productive yourself.

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:46.220
You're making other people and
teams more productive as well.

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:48.630
If I could have done that,
I probably wouldn't have,

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:50.870
on my four-year
anniversary, said,

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:53.390
Brian, I need to move to
a strategic advisor role,

00:28:53.390 --> 00:28:56.160
because this is just too much.

00:28:56.160 --> 00:28:59.860
So with that, I'm now
going to open it up

00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:05.160
to questions from
you or from Dory.

