We said, what is it that we
want this company to look

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:39.360
like five years from now
in terms of scale and soul?

00:36:39.360 --> 00:36:41.910
And tangibly, what
does that mean?

00:36:41.910 --> 00:36:44.270
And then how do
we work backwards?

00:36:44.270 --> 00:36:47.480
And how do we actually have
people in the company who

00:36:47.480 --> 00:36:50.210
are the role models for both?

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:52.910
I mean the person who actually
has both within them--

00:36:52.910 --> 00:36:53.810
great.

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:55.040
And those people are--

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:57.770
the left can do the left
brain-right brain tango.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:36:59.942
But the person who is
actually right here

00:36:59.942 --> 00:37:02.150
and the person who's right
here-- how do we make sure

00:37:02.150 --> 00:37:04.640
they're on teams together?

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:08.900
And how do we actually look at
teams for cognitive diversity?

00:37:08.900 --> 00:37:11.000
Not just the demographic
diversity-- yes,

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.490
that's important-- but
cognitive diversity

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:15.650
is a really important
part of how do

00:37:15.650 --> 00:37:19.800
you help group think not occur.

00:37:19.800 --> 00:37:23.900
And so that's a long-winded
answer, but I hope that helps.

00:37:23.900 --> 00:37:25.370
AUDIENCE: So we're at Google.

00:37:25.370 --> 00:37:27.040
You were at Airbnb.

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:28.880
We've talked a lot
about Silicon Valley.

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:30.900
I'm wondering how you
would generalize this

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:33.340
to the rest of the country,
the rest of the world,

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:35.950
and how that might be different.

00:37:35.950 --> 00:37:38.830
CHIP CONLEY: Well, here's the
thing, because people sometimes

00:37:38.830 --> 00:37:40.330
say, well, this is
just your Airb--

00:37:40.330 --> 00:37:43.110
this is just your technology,
Silicon Valley bubble.

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:43.690
And I was like, you know what?

00:37:43.690 --> 00:37:46.106
Seven of the 10 most valuable
companies in the world today

00:37:46.106 --> 00:37:47.484
are tech companies.

00:37:47.484 --> 00:37:49.150
All companies want
to be tech companies.

00:37:49.150 --> 00:37:51.430
I mean I was at
Procter and Gamble

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:53.230
two months ago in their
headquarters, spent

00:37:53.230 --> 00:37:56.510
three days with the CEO, senior
team, did a bunch of things

00:37:56.510 --> 00:37:57.130
there.

00:37:57.130 --> 00:37:59.170
Procter and Gamble wants
to be a tech company.

00:37:59.170 --> 00:38:02.890
And what I mean by this
is what's going on here

00:38:02.890 --> 00:38:04.340
and what goes on
in the tech world

00:38:04.340 --> 00:38:07.150
and what goes on in terms of
showing value, what companies

00:38:07.150 --> 00:38:11.020
actually create value,
frankly, in the stock market

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:12.940
is what all those
other companies

00:38:12.940 --> 00:38:14.920
want to actually imitate.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:17.870
So what I want to say is--

00:38:17.870 --> 00:38:20.530
and you see you it,
sometimes, in mistakes.

00:38:20.530 --> 00:38:24.340
Ford Motor Company
hired a 34-year-old CMO.

00:38:24.340 --> 00:38:27.880
Nothing wrong with hiring
a 34-year-old CMO, if they

00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:29.950
could actually do the job well.

00:38:29.950 --> 00:38:31.960
The person lasted about
a year and a half,

00:38:31.960 --> 00:38:33.860
and they didn't work out well.

00:38:33.860 --> 00:38:35.200
But someone else could have.

00:38:35.200 --> 00:38:39.730
But the question is, when we're
making decisions about leaders,

00:38:39.730 --> 00:38:42.580
are we making sure we're
asking enough questions

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:46.330
about their skill set beyond
what they're the expert at?

00:38:46.330 --> 00:38:49.120
Somebody could be an expert
at something particular,

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:51.760
and then they grow, because
they're so good at that,

00:38:51.760 --> 00:38:55.540
and they don't have the
balance of the other skills

00:38:55.540 --> 00:39:00.260
to actually pull off growing
in leadership like they do.

00:39:00.260 --> 00:39:03.340
So I would just say, I think
to answer your question,

00:39:03.340 --> 00:39:07.840
I think that Silicon Valley
is the model for a lot

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:09.244
of other companies out there.

00:39:09.244 --> 00:39:11.410
Is it true that there's
lots of old school companies

00:39:11.410 --> 00:39:12.070
that don't fit this?

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:12.570
Yes.

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:15.160
I was on a webinar this
morning, and someone

00:39:15.160 --> 00:39:18.569
from a manufacturing company
from Kansas was on the phone.

00:39:18.569 --> 00:39:20.110
And it was 200 people
in the company,

00:39:20.110 --> 00:39:22.510
and the company he
described is a company that

00:39:22.510 --> 00:39:24.340
felt like it's 50 years ago.

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:27.820
And it might work
fine in manufacturing.

00:39:27.820 --> 00:39:31.497
They've just started to think
about robotics in this company.

00:39:31.497 --> 00:39:33.580
A lot of companies started
to think about robotics

00:39:33.580 --> 00:39:34.670
30 years ago.

00:39:34.670 --> 00:39:36.580
But it seems to work for them.

00:39:36.580 --> 00:39:40.120
But that small company
in Kansas is not

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:42.250
the role model for a
lot of other companies

00:39:42.250 --> 00:39:43.130
around the world.

00:39:43.130 --> 00:39:46.160
So I think how we do
things here, we need to--

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:48.220
the more you know
your role model--

00:39:48.220 --> 00:39:49.720
it's like being a parent--

00:39:49.720 --> 00:39:52.310
the more you actually have
to watch your behavior.

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:53.130
So.

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:54.880
AUDIENCE: If I might
add another question.

00:39:54.880 --> 00:39:55.630
CHIP CONLEY: Yeah.

00:39:55.630 --> 00:39:57.460
AUDIENCE: For you
transitioning from being

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:02.890
CEO to being a mentor-intern,
what are some areas that you

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:05.890
needed to grow that you
found yourself saying, wow,

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:06.730
this is different?

00:40:06.730 --> 00:40:10.950
I maybe-- just some thoughts
on what you needed to improve

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:12.181
or what surprised you.

00:40:12.181 --> 00:40:13.930
CHIP CONLEY: Two things
I've already said,

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:14.980
and then I'll say others.

00:40:14.980 --> 00:40:17.920
One is my ego, just
right-sizing my ego,

00:40:17.920 --> 00:40:22.600
realizing that it was time for
me to actually focus on being

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:25.770
not interesting but interested.

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:30.160
And so I was very interested
in how I supported them,

00:40:30.160 --> 00:40:31.030
so that was one.

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:33.472
A second thing-- the
idea of being a learner

00:40:33.472 --> 00:40:34.930
and the idea of,
OK, I'm in my 50s.

00:40:34.930 --> 00:40:35.721
Maybe-- what is it?

00:40:35.721 --> 00:40:37.480
What would happen
if, in my 50s, I'm

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:40.000
having my biggest
decade of learning?

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:41.210
That was it as well.

00:40:41.210 --> 00:40:44.860
But I think beyond
that, I think one

00:40:44.860 --> 00:40:48.430
of the things that happens
with our brains as we get older

00:40:48.430 --> 00:40:49.160
is, yes--

00:40:49.160 --> 00:40:49.920
is true.

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:52.190
Our recall is not as
good as it used to be,

00:40:52.190 --> 00:40:54.806
so memory and
quickness goes away.

00:40:54.806 --> 00:40:56.680
But one thing that a
lot of people don't know

00:40:56.680 --> 00:41:01.894
is as your brain ages, you
start getting all wheel drive.

00:41:01.894 --> 00:41:03.310
All wheel drive
means you actually

00:41:03.310 --> 00:41:06.717
do the left brain-right
brain tango more easily.

00:41:06.717 --> 00:41:07.550
What does that mean?

00:41:07.550 --> 00:41:10.150
It means you actually
are able to move

00:41:10.150 --> 00:41:12.220
amongst your whole
brain more quickly

00:41:12.220 --> 00:41:14.560
and adeptly than when
you were younger,

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.030
when you were more focused.

00:41:16.030 --> 00:41:16.810
OK, what is that?

00:41:16.810 --> 00:41:18.790
What's the benefit of that?

00:41:18.790 --> 00:41:20.440
In a company, the
benefit is it means

00:41:20.440 --> 00:41:24.490
it gives you holistic, systemic
thinking that allows you

00:41:24.490 --> 00:41:27.030
to get the gist of something.

00:41:27.030 --> 00:41:31.700
So what I started to see
at Airbnb and with my "why"

00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:36.449
and "what if" questions was,
OK, I'm hearing something here.

00:41:36.449 --> 00:41:38.990
I'm not sure everybody else is
seeing the pattern recognition

00:41:38.990 --> 00:41:40.250
that I'm seeing.

00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:44.750
And therefore, I'm not
listening for the precision

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:45.929
of that particular thing.

00:41:45.929 --> 00:41:48.470
There are a lot of other people
in the room who will do that.

00:41:48.470 --> 00:41:51.030
I'm actually looking for
the holistic questions.

00:41:51.030 --> 00:41:53.440
And so that was a shift for me.

00:41:53.440 --> 00:41:55.130
I was a pre--

00:41:55.130 --> 00:41:57.200
I was very-- I was
focused on transformation

00:41:57.200 --> 00:41:59.910
at my old company.

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:04.555
But I became more and more of
a sort of bigger thinker, which

00:42:04.555 --> 00:42:06.680
can be dangerous if you're
just the bigger thinker,

00:42:06.680 --> 00:42:10.130
and you're not able to
give solutions as well.

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:15.890
But I think that that
shift into that sort of--

00:42:15.890 --> 00:42:18.440
the Socrates role, as
one person said to me.

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:20.480
Like you become a Socrates
talking to the p--

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:22.380
you know, walking
through Athens,

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:24.540
or he was in Greece, right?

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:25.040
Yeah.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:28.880
So you're asking really
interesting questions.

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:30.620
And I think that
was a shift for me,

00:42:30.620 --> 00:42:32.490
because, actually,
when I was younger,

00:42:32.490 --> 00:42:34.597
I wanted to be the smartest
person in the room,

00:42:34.597 --> 00:42:36.680
and, therefore, I actually
tried to be the fastest

00:42:36.680 --> 00:42:38.880
to answer the questions.

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:40.550
And that's what I would do.

00:42:40.550 --> 00:42:45.700
And actually, I wasn't doing
that at Airbnb as much, so.

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:47.450
AUDIENCE: I have one question.

00:42:47.450 --> 00:42:49.940
Regarding retirement,
what's your take

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:53.570
on knowing we're living longer
with a third third of life

00:42:53.570 --> 00:42:57.420
and wanting to do more, as we've
learned, and we're in our 50s

00:42:57.420 --> 00:42:59.220
and growing that way?

00:42:59.220 --> 00:43:01.910
Do you think that we need
to be rethinking retirement

00:43:01.910 --> 00:43:03.470
on the individual
level, or is it

00:43:03.470 --> 00:43:08.170
something more systemic to
have companies changing out

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:09.410
into a bigger movement?

00:43:09.410 --> 00:43:10.410
What's your take?

00:43:10.410 --> 00:43:12.076
CHIP CONLEY: Lots of
thoughts are there.

00:43:12.076 --> 00:43:13.130
Thank you, Rachel.

00:43:13.130 --> 00:43:17.240
So first of all, the way we've
defined life, historically,

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:21.290
is learn, earn, retire.

00:43:21.290 --> 00:43:24.890
Typically, learn until you're
25, earn until you're 65,

00:43:24.890 --> 00:43:27.510
and then retire until you die.

00:43:27.510 --> 00:43:30.500
That's the model
that I grew up with.

00:43:30.500 --> 00:43:32.870
If you're younger than 40
today, you might look at that

00:43:32.870 --> 00:43:34.280
and say, no way.

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:35.960
That's not my model.

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:36.860
And it's true.

00:43:36.860 --> 00:43:39.512
Young people have a whole
different perspective

00:43:39.512 --> 00:43:40.970
on their lives,
partly because they

00:43:40.970 --> 00:43:42.010
know they're going
to live longer,

00:43:42.010 --> 00:43:43.468
partly because
they're not climbing

00:43:43.468 --> 00:43:44.810
corporate ladders like we did.

00:43:44.810 --> 00:43:45.560
And it's all good.

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:47.999
I would just say,
for younger people,

00:43:47.999 --> 00:43:50.540
you've got the right thinking,
because there's also something

00:43:50.540 --> 00:43:53.390
called the U-curve of happiness,
which is when people actually

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:55.700
are least happy in life,
which is, typically--

00:43:55.700 --> 00:43:57.970
sorry to say for you
people in your 40s--

00:43:57.970 --> 00:43:59.390
it's in your 40s.

00:43:59.390 --> 00:44:02.750
But the less you actually
are locked into doing things

00:44:02.750 --> 00:44:05.360
that you didn't
necessarily want to do,

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:07.250
because it was just
the conventional path,

00:44:07.250 --> 00:44:09.890
the less likely you have
disappointment in your 40s.

00:44:09.890 --> 00:44:11.610
So what does all that mean?

00:44:11.610 --> 00:44:15.350
It means thinking of
your life as a portfolio

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:17.600
and being able to
curate your own life

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:21.110
and being a little bit
of a freelancer of how

00:44:21.110 --> 00:44:23.750
you think about it and
knowing that you're going to--

00:44:23.750 --> 00:44:26.240
you might take a year
off, do a sabbatical

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:29.630
in your 40s or your 30s,
or you might go back

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:32.240
to school in your 50s.

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:35.210
All of that is on the table
today, and all of that's

00:44:35.210 --> 00:44:38.780
good, because what I
think we're going to see

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:42.640
is more and more people in
their 70s in the workplace.

00:44:42.640 --> 00:44:43.880
And that may sound weird.

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:45.920
Like, the person who
checked me in at my hotel

00:44:45.920 --> 00:44:47.940
was a 75-year-old.

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:50.820
You know, we're going
to see more of that.

00:44:50.820 --> 00:44:53.600
Especially in this country
if our employment situation

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:55.880
is at what it is, and
immigration doesn't open

00:44:55.880 --> 00:44:58.940
up much, we are going to have
a necessity to actually find

00:44:58.940 --> 00:45:01.970
new sources of employees.

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:03.630
What does that
mean for companies?

00:45:03.630 --> 00:45:05.088
I think what it
means for companies

00:45:05.088 --> 00:45:07.910
is more and more companies need
to respect the fact that when

00:45:07.910 --> 00:45:10.910
people want to actually
start winding down,

00:45:10.910 --> 00:45:14.980
they don't want to just be on
the conveyor belt to a cliff.

00:45:14.980 --> 00:45:17.150
I was 100% an
employee last week,

00:45:17.150 --> 00:45:21.480
and this week, I'm 0%,
because I've retired.

00:45:21.480 --> 00:45:24.320
There's a lot of evidence that
shows that when people retire,

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:26.990
their health conditions
actually don't get better.

00:45:26.990 --> 00:45:28.970
They actually get worse.

00:45:28.970 --> 00:45:30.930
And there's a lot
of reasons for that.

00:45:30.930 --> 00:45:32.360
So what do I think that means?

00:45:32.360 --> 00:45:34.520
I think the idea of people
moving from five days

00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:38.000
a week to three days a week,
and maybe then two days

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:41.060
a week over the course
of three or four years

00:45:41.060 --> 00:45:43.440
is something for
companies to consider.

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:45.080
Additionally,
especially for those

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:48.350
people who have great
institutional wisdom,

00:45:48.350 --> 00:45:50.150
because that
institutional wisdom--

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:52.400
I mean that's my
role at Airbnb now.

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:54.740
I'm an old timer at Airbnb
not because of my age,

00:45:54.740 --> 00:45:58.250
but because I was the 350th
employee in that company that

00:45:58.250 --> 00:46:01.040
now has 5,000 employees
five and 1/2 years later.

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:06.740
And only 100 of the 350 are
still there, so the fact

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:09.620
that I'm a strategic advisor,
and when I come to the office,

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:11.270
I am pulled in
different directions,

00:46:11.270 --> 00:46:13.910
because the people know I
have a little bit of awareness

00:46:13.910 --> 00:46:16.730
of how that works
or this works is

00:46:16.730 --> 00:46:18.870
a good thing for the company.

00:46:18.870 --> 00:46:21.160
So thanks for the question.

