of "Wired" magazine,

00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:47.040
66 years old, talking to a
bunch of, generally, people

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:50.430
in their 20s and 30s about
the future of technology.

00:47:50.430 --> 00:47:54.090
And then right after him was a
guy named Ryan Holliday onstage

00:47:54.090 --> 00:47:57.180
who has written a lot
of books about wisdom.

00:47:57.180 --> 00:47:59.310
So it was the 31-year-old
talking about wisdom

00:47:59.310 --> 00:48:01.690
and the 66-year-old
talking about technology.

00:48:01.690 --> 00:48:05.130
So let's be clear, this
is not across the board.

00:48:05.130 --> 00:48:06.970
Everybody doesn't
fit this profile.

00:48:06.970 --> 00:48:09.030
I think the bigger question is--

00:48:09.030 --> 00:48:13.170
that you ask, Karen--
is, how do you

00:48:13.170 --> 00:48:16.350
figure out what it
is you have to offer

00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:19.600
or what it is that you're
looking for from someone else?

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.140
And I think the
subtleties of that

00:48:22.140 --> 00:48:26.760
so often have to do with
what you see in a meeting.

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:30.000
It literally could be somebody
who runs a great meeting,

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:31.920
and so this is not
an EQ for DQ thing.

00:48:31.920 --> 00:48:34.470
It's just like, that person
runs a great meeting,

00:48:34.470 --> 00:48:36.444
and I have a hard
time running meetings.

00:48:36.444 --> 00:48:37.860
I'm just going to
see if they want

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:40.080
to have some coffee
and just talk with them

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:47.970
about, what are their four or
five best practices for running

00:48:47.970 --> 00:48:48.990
a meeting?

00:48:48.990 --> 00:48:50.400
Or it could be something else.

00:48:50.400 --> 00:48:53.220
I mean the specifics
of it aren't important.

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:55.410
What's relevant
is the willingness

00:48:55.410 --> 00:48:58.620
to go and ask
someone else if they

00:48:58.620 --> 00:49:01.170
could give you some tutelage.

00:49:01.170 --> 00:49:06.690
And I think the more we create
the culture in companies, where

00:49:06.690 --> 00:49:10.170
people feel like that's OK, and
the idea of mutual mentorship

00:49:10.170 --> 00:49:14.130
might grow out of that,
that's all we can ask for.

00:49:14.130 --> 00:49:17.490
AUDIENCE: Tribal knowledge
versus institutional wisdom--

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:19.440
when you said, "institutional
wisdom," I heard

00:49:19.440 --> 00:49:20.655
tribal knowledge and--

00:49:20.655 --> 00:49:21.375
CHIP CONLEY: Did you
say "tribal" or--

00:49:21.375 --> 00:49:21.810
AUDIENCE: Tribal.

00:49:21.810 --> 00:49:22.310
Tribal.

00:49:22.310 --> 00:49:23.720
CHIP CONLEY: Tribal, OK.

00:49:23.720 --> 00:49:24.700
Yeah.

00:49:24.700 --> 00:49:25.950
AUDIENCE: Just the modalities.

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:27.570
You keep talking
about mutual meeting

00:49:27.570 --> 00:49:30.150
face-to-face, mutual
collaboration,

00:49:30.150 --> 00:49:32.230
mentorship kind of arrangement.

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:34.150
How about the other
modalities of-- like,

00:49:34.150 --> 00:49:35.610
we talk about
knowledge transferred

00:49:35.610 --> 00:49:41.370
teaching seminars versus
writing documents and things.

00:49:41.370 --> 00:49:43.840
What has your experience
been of the balance

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:46.980
of getting wisdom
effectively communicated

00:49:46.980 --> 00:49:49.424
through other forms
than just face-to-face?

00:49:49.424 --> 00:49:51.090
CHIP CONLEY: You know,
we live in an era

00:49:51.090 --> 00:49:54.300
where you better have other
forms available to you,

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:54.900
for sure.

00:49:54.900 --> 00:49:55.930
I mean I think the--

00:49:59.130 --> 00:50:00.870
a few years ago, after
I sold my company,

00:50:00.870 --> 00:50:04.860
I created a company
called Fest300, Fest300.

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:08.400
And the whole company was
based upon the 300 best

00:50:08.400 --> 00:50:09.600
festivals in the world.

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:12.660
And so I went around to some
of the world's best festivals,

00:50:12.660 --> 00:50:16.410
because what I believed is
that in the era of URLs,

00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:19.380
that IRL experiences, in
real life experiences,

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:21.120
had something to teach us.

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:24.210
So you have to acknowledge
that my bias is

00:50:24.210 --> 00:50:27.900
quite strongly the IRL
experience of in real life.

00:50:27.900 --> 00:50:29.640
And part of the
reason for that is

00:50:29.640 --> 00:50:32.010
because there's the kinds of--

00:50:32.010 --> 00:50:34.632
our mirror neurons
work differently

00:50:34.632 --> 00:50:36.840
when we're face to face with
someone than, literally,

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:39.760
when we have a screen, and
we're doing a video call.

00:50:39.760 --> 00:50:41.160
So I think that there's that.

00:50:41.160 --> 00:50:46.800
There's also just the sense
that you can see subtleties

00:50:46.800 --> 00:50:51.780
more easily in conversation,
when it's face-to-face.

00:50:51.780 --> 00:50:53.960
But let me say,
at the same time,

00:50:53.960 --> 00:50:58.680
that I think the technology
around how you understand

00:50:58.680 --> 00:51:01.310
who you're talking to and
what the experience is,

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:04.140
is probably so early
stage at this point,

00:51:04.140 --> 00:51:06.840
such that 10 years
from now, the ability

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:09.780
to have your mirror
neurons kicked

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:13.140
in more when you're talking
to someone when it's

00:51:13.140 --> 00:51:15.160
with a screen may be better.

00:51:15.160 --> 00:51:17.140
And there's no doubt the
scaling piece of this,

00:51:17.140 --> 00:51:19.264
if you're just talking
about one-on-one stuff, that

00:51:19.264 --> 00:51:20.380
doesn't scale very well.

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:23.580
So the process of
educating people

00:51:23.580 --> 00:51:26.670
in sort of a more webinar
kind of a format--

00:51:26.670 --> 00:51:27.560
that's fine.

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:29.600
I think the key on
everything, all of this,

00:51:29.600 --> 00:51:32.600
is about helping
people to understand,

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:36.060
what are their best
learning modalities.

00:51:36.060 --> 00:51:38.090
And we aren't taught
that in high school.

00:51:38.090 --> 00:51:40.580
We're not taught, are
we a visual thinker?

00:51:40.580 --> 00:51:44.750
Or what's the form of learning
that actually is best for us?

00:51:44.750 --> 00:51:47.360
If we could help people
understand that earlier,

00:51:47.360 --> 00:51:49.580
then I would say that the
question would be easier

00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:51.620
to answer, because
then you'd help people,

00:51:51.620 --> 00:51:55.740
steer them to that modality
that works best for them.

00:51:55.740 --> 00:51:57.680
So thank you.

00:51:57.680 --> 00:51:59.710
With that, that's
our hour together.

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:00.490
So thanks to--

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:00.750
KAREN: Thank you, Chip--

00:52:00.750 --> 00:52:03.249
CHIP CONLEY: --all of you and
all of you out there watching.

00:52:03.249 --> 00:52:07.120
[APPLAUSE]

